# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The **1966 Georgia gubernatorial election** was held in the U.S. state on November 8, 1966.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] After an election that exposed divisions within the Georgia Democratic Party (giving the Georgia Republican Party a shot at the Governor's Mansion for the first time in the twentieth century), segregationist Democrat Lester Maddox was elected Governor of Georgia.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The voting also brought future President Jimmy Carter to statewide prominence for the first time.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The election was the closest in Georgia gubernatorial history; Republican candidate Bo Callaway won a plurality of the popular vote, but lost the contingent election in the Georgia General Assembly to Maddox.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It was also the first time since 1916 that the Republican Party contested a gubernatorial election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] If Callaway had won the contingent election or a majority of the popular vote, he would have become the only Republican governor of Georgia in the 20th century.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2022, this is the last time that Dougherty, Macon, Randolph, Richmond, Stewart, and Talbot counties voted for the Republican candidate for governor, and the last time that Liberty County did not vote for the Democratic candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Former Governor Ernest Vandiver was considered the favorite to return to his former job (although governors could not then succeed themselves, they could run again after leaving office), but he dropped out of the race because of health problems.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] That opened the door for former Governor Ellis Arnall, former Lieutenant Governor Garland T.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Byrd, state Senator Jimmy Carter, and two segregationist businessmen, Lester Maddox and James H.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray Sr., to run for the Democratic nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray, a Massachusetts native, publisher of the *Albany Herald* and founder of what is now Gray Television, was a former Georgia Democratic state chairman who defended segregation in his northern accent before the 1960 Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In the primary race, Maddox had often called upon Gray to leave the race, having said that his opponent was "going down like the *Titanic*".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray remained in the race and finished fourth in the primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He declared neutrality in the Maddox-Arnall runoff election, not openly supporting either candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] However, one of Gray's associates, Roy V.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Harris of Augusta, a member of the Georgia State Board of Regents, supported Maddox over Arnall.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray supporters attempted to entice Maddox to leave the race with a $100,000 payment.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray denied involvement in the scheme but would not, on Maddox's request, take a lie detector test.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The primary was held on September 13, 1966.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Pursuant to Georgia law, as no candidate received a majority of votes in the primary, a runoff was held on September 27.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Smith was the Democratic nominee for Lieutenant Governor of Georgia, after he defeated incumbent Peter Zack Geer in the primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He was the first Republican Representative from Georgia since Reconstruction.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] No other Republicans sought down-ballot constitutional offices.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] State Senator Holden Eugene "Gene" Sanders of DeKalb County, a moderate Republican, sought to run for lieutenant governor, but Callaway said that Sanders did not follow the proper procedures.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The Republican strategy was to shun all other statewide races for fear that a full ticket would unify the Democrats.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The *Atlanta Journal*, which ultimately endorsed Callaway, claimed that key Republicans were a clique who hoped to build the party from the governor's office.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The *Athens Daily News* depicted traditional Georgia Republican leaders as "would-be politicians [who viewed the party as] personal property and who made no real effort to expand into a broad-based and effective political organization".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Some people were unhappy with both major nominees and took the "Go Bo" of Callaway's campaign, expanding it to "Go Bo, and take Lester with you".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Under Georgia law at the time, the Georgia General Assembly would be required to hold a contingent election if no candidate received a majority of the popular vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Persons opposed to the contingent election procedure filed an action in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia, contending that a contingent election would violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The three-judge federal district court declared the Georgia contingent procedure unconstitutional and void on November 17, 1966, but less than a month later, on December 12, 1966, the United States Supreme Court reversed, and the contingent election went forward.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Maddox was elected on the first ballot despite losing the popular vote by 0.31%.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The **1970 Georgia gubernatorial election** was held in the U.S. state on November 3, 1970.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It was marked by the election as Governor of Georgia of the relatively little-known former state senator Jimmy Carter after a hard battle in the Democratic primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] This election is famous because Carter, who was often regarded as one of the New South Governors, later ran for president in 1976 on his gubernatorial record and won.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2026, this was the last time Fulton County was carried by the Republican candidate in a gubernatorial election, the only time it failed to back Carter, and the last time a Democrat in any race won without carrying it.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It is also the last time that Clarke County voted for the Republican candidate for governor.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Under the Georgia constitution of 1945, incumbent Democratic governor Lester Maddox was prohibited from seeking re-election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Initially the strongest candidate was former governor Carl E.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Sanders was a moderate, who worked to improve education, the environment and led the transition away from racial segregation with cooperation with the United States Federal Government.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He left office at the peak of his popularity.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] His main opponent was former state senator and candidate for the gubernatorial nomination in 1966 Jimmy Carter.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Despite Sanders's initial front-runner status and popularity, Carter won by nearly 20 points.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Governor Maddox ran for lieutenant governor and won the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] At this time, Georgia was still regarded as a part of the Democratic Party's Solid South, despite the Republican plurality in the 1966 gubernatorial race.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic position in 1970 was again regarded as safe.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] TV newsman Hal Suit faced Comptroller James L.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Bentley, who had been elected as a Democrat but joined the Republican party in 1968.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] While he refused to join the segregationist White Citizens' Council, he ran a campaign specifically designed to win over the segregationist vote that had made Maddox governor four years earlier.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter's true feelings about race might be better indicated by the fact that his had been one of only two families which voted to admit blacks to the Plains Baptist Church, but that was not something advertised in the 1970 race for governor.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to this campaign, Jimmy Carter appeared to be a proponent of civil rights and desegregation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In 1954 he refused to join the White Citizens Council despite immense pressure and went on to vote against segregation for his church in 1965.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] However, after failing to run as a moderate in the Georgia Gubernatorial Election of 1966, Carter's new strategy in 1970 was designed to attract the pro-segregationist vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Poll data suggested that the appearance of a pro-segregationist position could be critical to winning the race, even if it was never overtly stated.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In order to shore up segregationist support, Carter made overtures to numerous racial organizations, and even personally called the cofounder of the White Citizens Council.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter's apparent support for segregation sparked animosity with his opponent Carl Sanders.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Sanders claims that when his own campaign had presented the same poll data, he refused to pursue a strategy on it for moral reasons.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Furthermore, Carter's campaign printed numerous pamphlets insinuating Sanders was too "chummy" with Black Americans.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Ultimately, Carter himself has expressed embarrassment and regret over his strategy.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter won praise for his strategy from Leroy Johnson, who stated "I understand why he ran that kind of ultra-conservative campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The **1972 Democratic National Convention** was the presidential nominating convention of the Democratic Party for the 1972 presidential election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] It was held at Miami Beach Convention Center in Miami Beach, Florida, also the host city of the Republican National Convention that year, on July 10–13, 1972.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] O'Brien served as permanent chairman of the convention, while Yvonne Braithwaite Burke served as vice-chair, becoming the first African American and the first woman of color to hold that position.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] On the last day of the convention, Lawrence F.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] O'Brien departed and Burke was left to preside for about fourteen hours.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated Senator George McGovern of South Dakota for president and Senator Thomas Eagleton of Missouri for vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eagleton withdrew from the race just 19 days later after it was disclosed that he had previously undergone mental health treatment, including electroshock therapy, and he was replaced on the ballot by Sargent Shriver of Maryland, a Kennedy in-law.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which has been described as "a disastrous start to the general election campaign", was one of the most unusual—perhaps the most contentious in the history of the Democratic Party since 1924—with sessions beginning in the early evening and lasting until sunrise the next morning.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Previously excluded political activists gained influence at the expense of elected officials and traditional core Democratic constituencies such as organized labor.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] A protracted vice presidential nominating process delayed McGovern's acceptance speech (which he considered "the best speech of his life") until 2:48 a.m.—after most television viewers had gone to bed.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The 1972 convention was significant as the first implementation of the reforms set by the Commission on Party Structure and Delegate Selection, which McGovern himself had chaired before deciding to run for president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] After McGovern resigned from his position as chair, he was replaced as chair by U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Representative Donald Fraser, which gave the McGovern–Fraser Commission its name.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The 28-member commission was established after the tumultuous 1968 convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] In addition, there were new rules ensuring that party meetings in non-rural areas were held on uniform dates, at uniform times, and in places of easy access and that adequate public notice of all party meetings concerned with delegate selection was posted.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Among the most significant of the changes were new quotas mandating that certain percentages of delegates be women or members of minority groups.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] As a result of the new rules, subjects that were previously deemed not fit for political debate, such as abortion and gay rights, now occupied the forefront of political discussion.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The new rules for choosing and seating delegates created an unusual number of rules and credentials challenges.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Many traditional Democratic groups such as organized labor and big-city political machines had small representation at the convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Many traditional Democratic leaders and politicians felt that McGovern's delegate count did not reflect the wishes of most Democratic voters.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Georgia Governor Jimmy Carter helped to spearhead a "Stop McGovern" campaign, while at the same time trying to become McGovern's candidate for vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The stop-McGovern forces tried unsuccessfully to alter the delegate composition of the California delegation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Illinois primary required voters to select individual delegates, not presidential candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Most Illinois delegation members were uncommitted and were controlled or influenced by Chicago Mayor Richard J.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Daley, the leader of the Chicago political machine.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The delegation was challenged by McGovern supporters arguing that the results of the primary did not create a diverse enough delegation in terms of women and minorities.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee, headed by Patricia Roberts Harris, rejected the entire elected delegation, including elected women and minorities, and seated an unelected delegation led by Chicago Alderman William Singer and Jesse Jackson, pledged to George McGovern.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The California primary was "winner-take-all", which was contrary to the delegate selection rules.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] So even though McGovern only won the California primary by a 5% electoral margin, he won all 271 of their delegates to the convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The anti-McGovern group argued for a proportional distribution of the delegates, while the McGovern forces stressed that the rules for the delegate selection had been set and the Stop McGovern alliance was trying to change the rules after the game.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee ruled in favor of the anti-McGovern group prior to the convention, leaving McGovern short of a first-ballot majority.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] However, the committee was overruled by a floor vote on the first day of the convention and a unanimous McGovern delegation was seated.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern recognized the mixed results of the changes that he made to the Democratic nominating convention, saying, "I opened the doors of the Democratic Party and 20 million people walked out".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The so-called "magic number", or number of delegates needed to secure the nomination, was 1,509.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Formed after "divisive platform battles", the 1972 Democratic National Convention's platform has been characterized as "probably the most liberal one ever adopted by a major party in the United States".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] It advocated immediate withdrawal from Vietnam, amnesty for war resisters, the abolition of the draft, a guaranteed job for all Americans (it offered to "make the government the employer of last resort"), and a guaranteed family income well above the poverty line.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Feminist Movement was a major influence on the Democratic platform of 1972, and on the entire convention in general.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] With renewed vigor, the Democrats reaffirmed their dedication to the Equal Rights Amendment, as did the Republicans.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] There were disagreements within the Democrats of the National Women's Political Caucus (NWPC), and the Women's Movement in general, over how to best approach certain issues.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] At the convention Betty Friedan clashed with Gloria Steinem over the way NWPC women should approach certain issues, and whether or not they should make sure to throw all possible support behind Shirley Chisholm (both women were supporters of Chisholm's presidential campaign).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] As the convention was occurring on Miami Beach, Gloria Steinem chose The Betsy Ross Hotel as headquarters for the National Organization for Women (NOW).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Built in 1942, the hotel had been named after Betsy Ross, the Philadelphia seamstress who sewed American Flags.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern ultimately excised the abortion issue from the party's platform; recent publications show McGovern was deeply conflicted on the issue.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Actress and activist Shirley MacLaine, though privately supporting abortion rights, urged the delegates to vote against the plank.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Germaine Greer flatly contradicted Steinem's account.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Having recently gained public notoriety for her feminist manifesto *The Female Eunuch* and sparring with Norman Mailer, Greer was commissioned to cover the convention for *Harper's Magazine*.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer criticized Steinem's "controlled jubilation" that 38% of the delegates were women, ignoring that "many delegations had merely stacked themselves with token females...The McGovern machine had already pulled the rug out from under them".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer leveled her most searing critique on Steinem for her capitulation on abortion rights.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer reported, "Jacqui Ceballos called from the crowd to demand abortion rights on the Democratic platform, but Bella [Abzug] and Gloria stared glassily out into the room", thus killing the abortion rights platform.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer asks, "Why had Bella and Gloria not helped Jacqui to nail him on abortion?
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] What reticence, what loserism had afflicted them?" The cover of *Harper's* that month read, "Womanlike, they did not want to get tough with their man, and so, womanlike, they got screwed".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] A coalition of gay rights groups at the convention "drew up a proposed platform provision that called for, among other things, repealing laws against homosexuals marrying".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The provision was rejected by a vote of 54–34.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Afterwards, however, two delegates, Jim Foster and Madeline Davis (the first openly lesbian delegate to a major national political convention), spoke publicly on its behalf.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The platform championed busing under its "Education" plank, stating, "Transportation of students is another tool to accomplish desegregation".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The McGovern platform is often criticized as a "reformist coup" responsible in large part for the subsequent decline in American liberalism and chasing away the Democratic Party's "best politicians".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] It alienated the "working- and lower-middle class voters [who] saw [the platform] as threatening to traditional, deeply valued, if inequitable social arrangements"—so much so that one in three Democrats voted for Nixon, the Republican incumbent, in the presidential election in November.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Democrats also included "the right to be different" in their 1972 platform.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] According to the party, this right included the right to "maintain a cultural or ethnic heritage or lifestyle, without being forced into a compelled homogeneity".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Most polls showed McGovern running well behind incumbent President Richard Nixon, except when McGovern was paired with Massachusetts Senator Ted Kennedy.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern and his campaign brain trust lobbied Kennedy heavily to accept the bid to be McGovern's running mate, but he continually refused their advances, and instead suggested U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Representative (and House Ways and Means Committee chairman) Wilbur Mills of Arkansas and Boston Mayor Kevin White.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Offers were then made to Hubert Humphrey, Connecticut Senator Abraham Ribicoff, and Minnesota Senator Walter Mondale, all of whom turned it down.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern and his campaign staff felt that a Kennedy-style figure was best to balance the ticket: a Catholic, big city-based leader with strong ties to organized labor and urban political machines.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Immediately, White was dropped from consideration.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Finally, the vice presidential slot was offered to Senator Thomas Eagleton of Missouri, who was relatively unknown to many of the delegates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] By the time the roll call finally began, many of the delegates were angry and wary after the protracted infighting, and combined with the last-day-of-school atmosphere of the proceedings, caused the vice-presidential balloting to become nothing short of a farce.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The delegates cast ballots for a record 79 people, including many not involved in politics, as well as three deceased persons, Chinese leader Mao Zedong, and the fictional Archie Bunker.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] As the vote went on, Farenthold began to attract an unexpected level of support, eventually leading to something of a grassroots campaign to nominate her over Eagleton.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] However, this ultimately proved too late and too disorganized to have any serious chance of denying Eagleton the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eventually, Eagleton secured the nomination at 1:40 a.m.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] This delay forced the acceptance speeches of the candidates to be given well past the television prime time hours, and probably hurt the McGovern campaign by not creating the so-called "convention bounce".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Several days after the convention, it was revealed that Senator Eagleton had been hospitalized for depression and had electric shock treatment, and was also rumored to be more than a social drinker.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern stood behind his choice and stated that he was behind Senator Eagleton "1000 percent".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The news media and many political pros, especially in the Democratic Party, lobbied hard for his removal from the ticket.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eventually, McGovern felt compelled to accept Senator Eagleton's withdrawal from the ticket.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] The episode had placed McGovern in a "no-win" situation: if he kept Eagleton, the selection did not look good for the decision-making ability of the McGovern team, while if he removed Eagleton, he appeared to be weak and vacillating.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] Since this incident, front-running presidential candidates have developed short lists of potential running mates, and have meticulously performed background checks.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern chose Sargent Shriver as his running mate a few weeks later: the McGovern-Shriver ticket went on to win electoral votes in only Massachusetts and D.C., and lost the election to incumbents Richard Nixon and Spiro Agnew by the largest percentage of the vote since 1936.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The **1976 Democratic National Convention** met at Madison Square Garden in New York City, from July 12 to July 15, 1976.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The assembled United States Democratic Party delegates at the convention nominated former Governor Jimmy Carter of Georgia for president and Senator Walter Mondale of Minnesota for vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] John Glenn and Barbara Jordan gave the keynote addresses.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] Jordan's keynote address made her the first African-American woman to deliver the keynote address at a Democratic National Convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The convention was the first in New York City since the 103-ballot 1924 convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] Carter easily won the nomination on the first ballot.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] He then chose Mondale, a liberal and a protégé of Hubert Humphrey, as his running mate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] Mondale was put over the top at roll call by the convention's second youngest delegate Cathy Clardy who cast the delegate votes for the State of Minnesota.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The Carter–Mondale ticket went on to win the 1976 presidential election on November 2.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The convention is also notable for the fact that congresswoman Lindy Boggs, who presided over it, thus became the first woman to preside over a national political convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The Democrats' 1976 platform called for continued price controls on natural gas, a policy which had caused dwindling domestic natural gas reserves since 1974 and which President Gerald Ford was asking to rescind.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] Despite an address from anti-abortion activist Erma Clardy Craven, the platform added "it is undesirable to attempt to amend the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] The following people had their names placed in nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] According to Jimmy Carter, his top choices for vice president were: Walter Mondale, Edmund Muskie, Frank Church, Adlai Stevenson III, John Glenn, and Henry M.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-national-convention] In his acceptance speech, Mondale diverted from his printed text which echoed John F.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] From January 27 to June 8, 1976, voters of the Democratic Party chose its nominee for president in the 1976 United States presidential election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Former Georgia governor Jimmy Carter was selected as the nominee through a series of primary elections and caucuses culminating in the 1976 Democratic National Convention held from July 12 to July 15, 1976, in New York City.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The primaries took place after the Watergate scandal and the subsequent Democratic landslide in the 1974 midterm elections.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Going into the presidential election, the Democratic Party stood a strong chance of recapturing control of the White House.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Hoping to avoid a repeat of 1972, Democrats nominated centrist Georgia governor Jimmy Carter to reclaim the Solid South and win back northern working-class voters.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] He ultimately defeated President Gerald Ford by a narrow margin, which was the only Democratic presidential win from 1968 until 1988.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] In 1972, Senator George McGovern seized the Democratic nomination through an early campaign and superior organization, aided by his inside knowledge of the reforms under a commission he chaired.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] McGovern, widely seen as an extremely liberal candidate, lost the general election in a historic landslide to incumbent Richard Nixon, carrying only the state of Massachusetts.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] During the 1972 campaign, several men were arrested for a break-in at the Watergate complex, home of the Democratic National Committee headquarters.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] As the investigation continued, it became clear that the break-in was one of several tactics utilized by the Nixon campaign against their political opponents.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The scandal and the subsequent attempt to cover it up eventually forced President Nixon to resign from office under political pressure and the threat of impeachment.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Nixon was succeeded by Gerald Ford, whom he had appointed to the Vice Presidency after Spiro Agnew himself resigned under investigation for bribery.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] As a result of the Watergate scandal and other scandals, the American withdrawal from Vietnam, and an ongoing economic recession, the Democratic Party won a major landslide in the 1974 midterm elections.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The post-Watergate political environment also led to a tightening of campaign finance regulations, the creation of the Church Committee to investigate abuses by federal intelligence agencies, and a general opposition to Washington and establishment politicians.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Much of the speculation for the 1976 nomination surrounded Senator Hubert Humphrey of Minnesota, formerly Vice President of the United States and the party's nominee in 1968.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Humphrey had won the largest number of votes in the 1972 primaries but lost in a bitter fight with McGovern.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Though Humphrey ultimately declined to seek the nomination again, many early votes went to uncommitted delegates who supporters hoped would commit to Humphrey by the time of the convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Senator Henry “Scoop” Jackson raised his national profile by speaking out on Soviet Union–United States relations and Middle East policy regularly, and was considered a front-runner for the nomination when he announced the start of his campaign in February 1975.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson received substantial financial support from Jewish-Americans who admired his pro-Israel views, but Jackson's support of the Vietnam War resulted in hostility from the left wing of the Democratic Party.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson chose to run on social issues, emphasizing law and order and his opposition to busing.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson was also hoping for support from labor, but the possibility that Hubert Humphrey might enter the race caused unions to offer only lukewarm support.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The 1976 campaign was the first presidential campaign in which the primary system was dominant.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] However, most of the Democratic candidates failed to realize the significance of the increased number of primaries, or the importance of creating momentum by winning the early contests.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jimmy Carter, who was virtually unknown at the national level, leveraged his obscurity to run as an "outsider" to Washington.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Carter's plan was to run in all of the primaries and caucuses, beginning with the Iowa caucuses, and build up momentum by winning "somewhere" each time primary elections were held.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 14,508 votes for Unpledged slate of Delegates at (37.16%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Only half the vote was accounted for in those sources found.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Though nearly complete, still a partial result.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] This is a partial result from 70 of Mississippi's 82 counties.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 9,803 Write-In votes for "None of the Above" at (1.33%), and 1,623 Write-In votes for Senator Edward Kennedy at (0.22%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] These are partial results; only 2,780 precincts of 6,100 were accounted for here.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The Delegate vote is not currently known.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The Uncommitted Delegates here represent a number of different camps.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The largest with 85 delegates was controlled Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, who had used Senator Adlai Stevenson III as a stand-in.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] 18 truly uncommitted delegates were divided into two camps, one led by congressman Paul Simon and the other by state treasurer Alan Dixon, both inclined to supporting Hubert Humphrey's potential entrance into the race.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The final 4 were pledged to Governor Daniel Walker, who had been engaged in a number of power struggles with Richard Daley..
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Returns from 28 counties with 56 delegates are not accounted for.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The Caucus was initially held in two phases due to fighting which disrupted the first round on February 22, resulting in a second round being held on this date.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] However, supporters of Carter opted to not participate in the second round, initially allowing Jackson supporters to win the remainder of the delegates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] To head off a dispute before the Convention, a compromise was reached in which the delegation would be divided as shown below.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The situation in New York is complicated in that the rather than voting for the candidates themselves, voters were instead voting for the individual delegates; it wasn't uncommon for the allegiance of some of these delegates to be ill-defined.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 7,154 votes for "None of the Names Shown" at (0.97%), and 14,473 Write-In votes at (1.95%); the Write-Ins were not broken down on the State level.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Only five of eight districts held conventions on this date.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 797 votes for Uncommitted Delegates at (2.99%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Remaining three of eight districts that hadn't held conventions back in April.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] As majorities were required, run-offs were held later (May 25th) in those delegate primaries that only resulted in a plurality.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] These are counties that did not hold their County Conventions on April 21st.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 7,199 votes for Senator Ted Kennedy and 1,467 scattered Write-Ins.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] By law the delegates were Uncommitted, regardless of the result of the primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] These were run-offs for those races on May 4th in which a majority was not reached.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 11,962 votes for an Uncommitted slate at (3.91%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 10,983 votes for Senator Ted Kennedy at (2.54%), 1,389 Write-In votes for Ronald Reagan at (0.32%), and 691 Write-In votes for Gerald Ford at (0.16%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Includes 11,962 votes for an Uncommitted slate at (1.84%).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] All votes are for Ohio State Treasurer Gertrude Donahey.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] At multiple times during the primaries, Humphrey hinted at a campaign for the nomination and expressed his willingness to be drafted, but ultimately declined to actively seek the nomination on April 29, after Carter's victory in Pennsylvania.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Several unsuccessful draft movements were formed and many uncommitted delegates expressed their preference for Humphrey.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Gallup did not break down results for other candidates individually.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] With no clear front-runner for the nomination and a political climate that seemed tilted heavily in their party's favor, a record number of Democrats competed for their party's presidential nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jimmy Carter startled many political experts by finishing second in the Iowa caucuses, behind only "uncommitted" delegates largely elected on the backs of minor candidates and Humphrey supporters.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Arizona Congressman Morris Udall, who had been leading in the polls at one point, came in fifth behind former Oklahoma Senator Fred R.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Harris, leading Harris to coin the term "winnowed in", referring to his surprisingly strong showing.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The New Hampshire primary was another victory for Carter, albeit one in which he was the lone moderate or conservative candidate in the field, both Jackson and Wallace choosing to bypass New Hampshire in favor of neighboring Massachusetts.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Thus, with the liberal vote split, Carter won.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The New Hampshire primary nevertheless had symbolic value for the Carter campaign, showing that a Southerner could appeal in New England in advance of the Massachusetts primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Among the liberal candidates in New Hampshire, Udall emerged as the leader.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] One week after the New Hampshire primary, Carter's campaign was dealt a serious blow in Massachusetts.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] With Jackson and Wallace joining the field to split moderate and conservative voters, Carter finished fourth, behind Jackson, Wallace, and Udall.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] None of the candidates campaigned heavily in the state, preferring to advertise on television.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson won the race by relying on experienced political activists, especially in Boston, and support from organized labor.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The week after Massachusetts, Carter righted the ship by defeating Wallace and Jackson in Florida.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The liberal candidates, with the exception of Milton Shapp, were not on the ballot and largely stayed out of the state; Jackson finished third.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson sought to capitalize on momentum from his victory in Massachusetts, but set expectations low given his poor polling in the state.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The campaign was acrimonious; Carter sought to maintain his status as the frontrunner by accusing Washington insiders of coordinating against him and accused Jackson of exploiting desegregation busing as an issue.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson countered with attacks on Carter's civil rights record as Governor.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Wallace, who had won Florida in 1972, staked his campaign on the state.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Carter then proceeded to slowly but steadily accumulate delegates in primaries around the nation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] In Illinois, the Democratic presidential candidates were overshadowed by a power struggle between Chicago mayor Richard J.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Daley won control of the delegation through a slate of delegates pledged to Senator Adlai Stevenson III, but among the declared candidates for the presidency, Carter won a convincing victory over Wallace in both the presidential preference primary and the separate delegate selection races.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Carter also knocked his key rivals out of the race one by one.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] He won a more dominant victory over Wallace in the North Carolina primary on March 23, winning his first majority in any state and thus neutralizing his main rival in the South.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] On April 6, Carter won a narrow come-from-behind victory in Wisconsin over Mo Udall, although Udall won the most delegates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson won a convincing victory over Udall in the New York primaries, but when Carter defeated Jackson in Pennsylvania on April 27, Jackson quit the race, citing a lack of funds.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] As Carter continued to gain momentum, a "Stop Carter" movement formed behind the late-starting campaigns of California Governor Jerry Brown and Senator Frank Church of Idaho.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Though neither candidate could secure the nomination themselves, they stood in the hopes of deadlocking the convention and denying Carter the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Now facing an organized opposition, Carter dropped several key Western primaries in May and June.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The 1976 Democratic National Convention was held in New York City.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] By the time the convention opened Carter already had more than enough delegates to win the nomination, and so the major emphasis at the convention was to create an appearance of party unity, which had been lacking in the 1968 and 1972 Democratic Conventions.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Carter easily won the nomination on the first ballot; he then chose Senator Walter Mondale of Minnesota, a liberal and a protege of Hubert Humphrey, as his running mate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] By June, Carter had the nomination sufficiently locked up and could take time to interview potential vice-presidential candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] The pundits predicted that Frank Church would be tapped to provide balance as an experienced senator with strong liberal credentials.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Church promoted himself, persuading friends to intervene with Carter in his behalf.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] If a quick choice had been required as in past conventions, Carter later recalled, he would probably have chosen Church.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] But the longer period for deliberation gave Carter time to worry about his compatibility with the publicity-seeking Church, who had a tendency to be long-winded.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Instead, Carter invited Senators Edmund Muskie, John Glenn and Walter Mondale, and Congressman Peter W.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Rodino to visit his home in Plains, Georgia, for personal interviews, while Church, Henry M.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Jackson, and Adlai Stevenson III would be interviewed at the convention in New York.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] Rodino revealed he had no interest in the position, and of all the other potential candidates, Carter found Mondale the most compatible.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] As a result, Carter selected Mondale as his running mate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] African American leadership within the Democratic Party had sought to potentially place Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley, Congressman Ron Dellums, or Congresswoman Barbara Jordan on the ticket with Carter.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-democratic-party-presidential-primaries] However, Jordan took herself out of consideration, and Carter did not have any interest in the other candidates put forward.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The **1976 United States presidential debates** were a series of debates held during the 1976 presidential election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The League of Women Voters organized four debates among the major party candidates, sponsored three presidential debates and one vice presidential debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] Three presidential debates were held between Republican nominee Gerald Ford and Democratic nominee Jimmy Carter.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] One vice presidential debate was held between their respective vice presidential running mates, Bob Dole and Walter Mondale.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] In each of the debates, the candidates received questions in turn with three minutes to answer and a 60-second rebuttal.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] In 1976 only the two candidates from the major political parties, Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter, were invited.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] As a result, only Bob Dole and Walter Mondale met the criteria for the vice presidential debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The first presidential debate between President Gerald Ford and former Governor Jimmy Carter took place on Thursday, September 23, 1976, in the Walnut Street Theater in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The debate was moderated by Edwin Newman of NBC, with a panel consisting of Elizabeth Drew, Frank Reynolds and James Gannon posed the questions to each candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] This was the first presidential debate in 16 years, and the first such debate to be televised in color.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] Eighty-one minutes into the broadcast of the 90 minute debate, the sound was lost and the debate was paused for 27 minutes before the problem was fixed and the debate could resume.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] An estimated 69.7 million viewers tuned into the debates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The second presidential debate between President Gerald Ford and former Governor Jimmy Carter took place on Wednesday, October 6, 1976, at the Palace of Fine Arts in San Francisco, California.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The debate was moderated by Pauline Frederick of NPR, who posed the questions for each candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] An estimated 63.9 million viewers tuned into the debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The only vice presidential debate between Senator Bob Dole and Senator Walter Mondale took place on Friday, October 15, 1976, in the Alley Theatre in Houston, Texas.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] It was the first vice presidential debate in American history.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] James Hoge of *Chicago Sun-Times* posed the questions for each candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] An estimated 43.2 million viewers tuned into the debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The third and final presidential debate between President Gerald Ford and former Governor Jimmy Carter took place on Friday, October 22, 1976, in the Phi Beta Kappa Memorial Hall at the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] The debate was moderated by Barbara Walters of ABC, who posed the questions for each candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-debates] An estimated 62.7 million viewers tuned into the debates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1976.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic ticket of former Georgia governor Jimmy Carter and Minnesota senior senator Walter Mondale narrowly defeated the Republican ticket of incumbent president Gerald Ford and Kansas junior senator Bob Dole.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election since 1932 in which the incumbent was defeated, as well as the only one of the six presidential elections from 1968 to 1988 to have the Democratic Party ticket win.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford ascended to the presidency when Richard Nixon resigned in 1974 in the wake of the Watergate scandal, which badly damaged the Republican Party and its electoral prospects.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford previously served as Nixon's second vice president after his first vice president, Spiro Agnew, resigned in 1973 due to a bribery scandal.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford promised to continue Nixon's political agenda and govern as a moderate Republican, causing considerable backlash from the conservative wing of his party.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford narrowly prevailed against former California governor Ronald Reagan in the Republican primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was unknown outside of his home state of Georgia at the start of the Democratic primaries, but he emerged as the front-runner after his victories in the first set of primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning as a political moderate within his own party and as a Washington outsider, Carter defeated numerous opponents to clinch the Democratic nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford pursued a "Rose Garden strategy" in which he sought to portray himself as an experienced leader focused on fulfilling his role as chief executive.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On the other hand, Carter emphasized his status as a reformer who was "untainted" by Washington.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Saddled with a poor economy, the fall of South Vietnam, and the political fallout from the Watergate scandal, including his unpopular pardon of Richard Nixon, Ford trailed by a wide margin in polls taken after Carter's formal nomination in July 1976.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's polling rebounded after a strong performance in the first presidential debate, and the race was close on election day.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter won the election with 297 Electoral College votes and took 50.1% of the popular vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He carried several Midwestern and Northeastern states along with every state in the Deep South, becoming the first Democrat to accomplish this feat since Franklin D.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter's narrow victories in Ohio and Wisconsin, which carried a combined 36 electoral votes, were crucial to his win.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, Ford swept the West Coast and Mountain states and took 48.0% of the popular vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford became the first president to have served without ever winning a national election as president or vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His loss to Carter was due in part to the backlash against Republican candidates nationwide in the wake of the Watergate scandal, a trend that became apparent in the 1974 elections.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The surprise winner of the 1976 Democratic presidential nomination was Jimmy Carter, a former state senator and governor of Georgia.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] When the primaries began, Carter was little-known at the national level, and many political pundits regarded a number of better-known candidates, such as Senator Henry M.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson from Washington, Representative Morris Udall from Arizona, Governor George Wallace of Alabama, and California Governor Jerry Brown, as the favorites for the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the wake of the Watergate scandal, Carter realized that his status as a Washington outsider, political centrist, and moderate reformer could give him an advantage over his better-known establishment rivals.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter also took advantage of the record number of state primaries and caucuses in 1976 to eliminate his better-known rivals one-by-one.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson made a fateful decision not to compete in the early Iowa caucus and New Hampshire primary, which Jimmy Carter won after liberals split their votes among four other candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Though Jackson went on to win the Massachusetts and New York primaries, he was forced to quit the race on May 1, after losing the critical Pennsylvania primary to Carter by twelve percentage points.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter then defeated Governor Wallace, his main conservative challenger, by a wide margin in the North Carolina primary, forcing Wallace to end his campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Representative Udall, a liberal, then became Carter's main challenger.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He finished second to Carter in the New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Wisconsin, New York, Michigan, South Dakota, and Ohio primaries, and won the caucuses in his home state of Arizona, while running even with Carter in the New Mexico caucuses.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, the fact that Udall finished second to Carter in most of these races meant that Carter steadily accumulated more delegates for the nomination than Udall did.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As Carter closed in on the nomination, an "ABC" ("Anybody But Carter") movement started among Northern and Western liberal Democrats who worried that Carter's Southern upbringing would make him too conservative for the Democratic Party.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The leaders of the "ABC" movement, Idaho Senator Frank Church and California Governor Jerry Brown, both announced their candidacies for the Democratic nomination, and defeated Carter in several late primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, their campaigns started too late to prevent Carter from gathering the remaining delegates he needed to capture the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] By June 1976, Carter had captured more than enough delegates to win the Democratic nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] At the 1976 Democratic National Convention, Carter easily won the nomination on the first ballot; Udall finished in second place.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter then chose Minnesota Senator Walter Mondale, a liberal, as his running mate.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The contest for the Republican Party's presidential nomination in 1976 was between two serious candidates: incumbent president Gerald Ford, a member of the party's moderate wing, and former governor of California Ronald Reagan, a member of the party's conservative wing.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The presidential primary campaign between the two men was hard-fought and relatively even; by the start of the Republican Convention in August 1976, the race for the nomination was still too close to call.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The 1976 Republican Convention was the last political convention to open with the presidential nomination still being undecided until the actual balloting at the convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The following graph depicts the standing of each candidate in the poll aggregators from January 1976 to Election Day.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] One of the advantages Ford held over Carter as the general election campaign began was his presidential privilege to preside over events celebrating the United States Bicentennial; this often resulted in favorable publicity for Ford.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] C., fireworks display on the Fourth of July, which was televised nationally.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On July 7, 1976, the President and First Lady served as hosts at a White House state dinner for Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip of the United Kingdom, which was televised on the Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) network.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] These events were part of Ford's "Rose Garden" strategy to win the election, meaning that instead of appearing as a typical politician, Ford presented himself as a "tested leader" who was busily fulfilling the role of national leader and chief executive.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Not until October did Ford leave the White House to actively campaign across the nation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter ran as a reformer who was "untainted" by Washington political scandals, which many voters found attractive in the wake of the Watergate scandal that had led to President Richard Nixon's resignation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford, although personally unconnected with Watergate, was seen by many as too close to the discredited Nixon administration, especially after he granted Nixon a presidential pardon for any crimes he might have committed during his term of office.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's pardon of Nixon caused his popularity, as measured by public opinion polls, to plummet.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's refusal to explain his reasons for pardoning Nixon publicly (he would do so in his memoirs several years later), also hurt his image.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford unsuccessfully asked Congress to end the 1950s-era price controls on natural gas, which had caused a dwindling of American natural gas reserves after the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter stated during his campaign that he opposed the ending of the price controls and thought such a move would be "disastrous".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] After the Democratic National Convention, Carter held a 33-point lead over Ford in the polls.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, as the campaign continued, the race greatly tightened.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign *Playboy* magazine published a controversial interview with Carter; in the interview, Carter admitted to having "lusted in my heart" for women other than his wife and used the word "screw," which cut into his support among women and evangelical Christians.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, Ford performed well in what was the first televised presidential debate since 1960.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Polls taken after the debate showed that most viewers felt that Ford was the winner.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was also hurt by Ford's charges that he lacked the necessary experience to be an effective national leader and that he was vague on many issues.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, Ford also committed a costly blunder in the campaign that halted his momentum.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the second presidential debate on October 6, Ford stumbled when he asserted that "there is no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe, and there never will be under a Ford administration".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He added that he did not "believe that the Poles consider themselves dominated by the Soviet Union", and made the same claim with regard to Yugoslavia and Romania (Yugoslavia was not a Warsaw Pact member).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford refused to retract his statement for almost a week after the debate, causing his surge in the polls to stall and allowing Carter to maintain a slight lead in the polls.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] A vice-presidential debate, the first formal one of its kind, between Bob Dole and Walter Mondale also hurt the Republican ticket when Dole asserted that military unpreparedness on the part of Democratic presidents was responsible for all of the wars the U.S. had fought in the 20th century.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Dole, a World War II veteran, noted that in every 20th-century war, from World War I to the Vietnam War, a Democrat had been president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Dole then pointed out that the number of U.S. casualties in "Democrat wars" was roughly equal to the population of Detroit.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Many voters felt that Dole's criticism was unfairly harsh, and that his dispassionate delivery made him seem cold.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Years later, Dole would remark that he regretted the comment, believing that it had hurt the Republican ticket.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] One factor that did help Ford in the closing days of the campaign was a series of popular television appearances he did with Joe Garagiola, a retired baseball player for the St.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Louis Cardinals and a well-known announcer for NBC Sports.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Garagiola and Ford appeared in a number of shows in several large cities.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the show, Garagiola would ask Ford questions about his life and beliefs; the shows were so informal, relaxed, and laid-back that some television critics labelled them the "Joe and Jerry Show".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford and Garagiola obviously enjoyed one another's company, and they remained friends after the election was over.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] There were three presidential debates and one vice presidential debate during the 1976 general election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his campaign's blunders, President Ford managed to close the remaining gap in the polls, and by election day, the race was judged to be even.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It took most of that night and the following morning to determine the winner.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was not until 3:30 am EST that NBC was able to declare that Carter had carried Mississippi and had thus accumulated more than the 270 electoral votes needed to win.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Seconds later, ABC also declared Carter the winner, based on projections for Carter in Wisconsin and Hawaii, while CBS announced Carter's victory at 3:45 am.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter defeated Ford by two percentage points in the national popular vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral vote was the closest since 1916; Carter carried 23 states, with 297 electoral votes, while Ford won 27 states, with 240 electoral votes (one elector, future state Senator Mike Padden from Washington state, pledged to Ford, voted for Reagan).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter's victory came primarily from his near-sweep of the South (he lost only Virginia and Oklahoma), and his narrow victories in large Northern states such as New York, Ohio, and Pennsylvania.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford did well in the West, carrying every state in that region, except for Hawaii.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The most tightly contested state in the election was Oregon, which Ford won by under 2,000 votes.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] By percentage of the vote, the states that secured Carter's victory were Wisconsin (1.68% margin) and Ohio (.27% margin).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Had Ford won these states and all other states he carried, he would have won the presidency.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The 27 states he won were, and still are, the most states ever carried by a losing candidate for president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Had Ford won the election, the provisions of the 22nd Amendment would have disqualified him from running again, as he served more than two years of Nixon's second term.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter became the first non-incumbent president representing a Southern state to be elected since Zachary Taylor in 1848.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of his loss, Ford became the most recent person to serve as president without ever being elected to the office, and the first since Chester A.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Both major-party vice-presidential nominees would later unsuccessfully run for President: Walter Mondale (Democratic) in 1984 and Bob Dole (Republican) in 1996.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was the first Democratic presidential nominee since John F.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Kennedy in 1960 to carry states in the Deep South (Bill Clinton was the only Democrat since 1976 to carry more than one state from the Deep South, doing so in 1992), and the only one since Lyndon B.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Johnson in 1964 to carry a majority of all southern states.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter performed very strongly in his home state of Georgia, carrying 66.7% of the vote and every county in the state.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His winning of 23 states was only the second time in history that the winner of the election won fewer than half the states (after 1960).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His 50.1% of the vote was the only time since 1964 that a Democrat managed to obtain an absolute majority of the popular vote in a presidential election until Barack Obama won 52.9% of the vote in 2008.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter is one of six Democrats since the American Civil War to obtain an absolute majority of the popular vote, the others being Samuel J.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the last time that a Democrat won the presidency without winning a number of modern blue states and swing states, specifically California, Connecticut, Illinois, Maine, Michigan, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New Mexico, Oregon, Vermont, and Washington.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only time a Democrat has won without New Mexico, as well as one of only two times it voted for a candidate who lost the popular vote, in addition to 2024.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Similarly, it is one of only three instances in which a Democrat won without Nevada (the others being the two elections of Grover Cleveland in 1884 and 1892).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats did not win without Iowa again until 2020.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time a winning Democrat won both Georgia and Florida.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] All future Democratic presidents won one of the two, but not both simultaneously.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first time in exactly 100 years when Florida and Virginia supported different candidates, and the first time since Oklahoma statehood in 1907 when Oklahoma and Tennessee did so.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the most recent election in which a losing Republican candidate carried any states in the Northeast.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As Carter won 319 more counties than Ford, this election would mark the last time a Democrat won a majority of counties.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1916 in which the winning candidate won fewer than 300 electoral votes; this would not happen again until 2000.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter also remains the last Democrat to win a presidential election while winning fewer than 300 electoral votes.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the last time until 2024 in which the popular vote margin in all 50 states and the District of Columbia swung in the same direction from the previous election, and the most recent in which they all swung Democratic.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the last election in which an incumbent president ran with a running mate who was not the incumbent vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in which all four major presidential and vice presidential candidates would at some point be their party's nominee for president and lose.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] In addition to Ford losing this election, Carter would lose reelection to Reagan in 1980, Mondale would lose to President Reagan in 1984, and Dole would lose to President Bill Clinton in 1996.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election represents the second time that the winning candidate has received a majority of the electoral votes while the second-place candidate carried a majority of the states.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It had previously happened in the 1960 election.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The "margin" column shows the difference between the two leading candidates, and the "swing" column shows the margin swing from the respective party's nominee from 1972 to 1976.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Maine allowed its electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/1976-united-states-presidential-election] With voters 30 years of age or older (born in 1946 or earlier) estimated by the exit poll to comprise 69% of the electorate, the Greatest Generation and the Silent Generation constituted the majority of the voting public.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act (ESA) was first passed in 1973 and forms the basis of biodiversity and endangered species protection in the United States.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The original purpose of the Endangered Species Act of 1973 was to prevent species endangerment and extinction due to the human impact on natural ecosystems.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The three most powerful sections of the ESA are Sections 4, 7 and 9.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 4 allows the Secretaries of Interior and Commerce to list species as threatened or endangered based on best available data.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 7 requires federal agencies to consult with Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) or National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) before taking any action that may threaten a listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Section 9 forbids the taking of an endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The first amendment to the ESA was passed by the 95th United States Congress in 1978 to "introduce some flexibility into the Endangered Species Act".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter case was an important test case of the ESA because it made Congress realize how powerful the ESA really was.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1966, the Tennessee Valley Authority began construction on the Tellico Dam on the Little Tennessee River.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] For years, environmentalists tried to shut down the project, but their actions were unsuccessful until the discovery of the snail darter, a small fish that feeds off aquatic snails.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The snail darter was listed as an endangered species in 1975 and part of the Little Tennessee River was designated as critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The completion of the Tellico Dam threatened the survival of the snail darter, which was thought to be native only to the Little Tennessee River.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1976, battle in the courts between the Tennessee Valley Authority and environmentalists began over the fate of the snail darter.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Over the next three years, the decision was appealed all the way to the Supreme Court.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Supreme Court ruled in favor of protecting the species "whatever the cost".
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The Endangered Species Act was clear in stating that no federal project should be exempt from the provisions of Section 7.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Starting in the spring of 1977, members of Congress made several attempts to pass legislation that weakened the ESA.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Many large business interest groups, including the mining and timber industries, also spoke out against the power of the ESA.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Beginning in April 1978, the Senate Subcommittee on Resources Protection began debating and developing a bill that would create a committee with power to exempt federal actions from Section 7 requirements.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On April 12, 1978 Senator John Culver (D-IA) and Senate Minority Leader Howard Baker (R-TN) introduced a bill that would create a seven-member Cabinet-level committee with the authority to exempt a federal agency from Section 7 requirements.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Meanwhile, in Wheatland, Wyoming, a consortium of energy utilities were attempting to build the Grayrocks Dam on the Laramie River to supply a coal-fired power plant.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Upset that water diversion would threaten the critically endangered whooping crane, on October 2, 1978, the Nebraska Attorney General’s office obtained a federal injunction barring the dam.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Grayrocks, however, enjoyed strong support in Congress, and by October 14 Teno Roncalio (D-WY) convinced the House to pass a bill exempting the dam from all federal regulation.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In lieu of that, Senator Culver (D-IA) adapted the bill to his own attempts to exempt the snail darter, creating the Endangered Species Committee and required the committee to decide on an exemption from protections of the snail darter and the whooping crane within 30 days.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Both the House of Representatives and Senate voted to amend the ESA, and on November 10 President Jimmy Carter signed the amendment into law.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On December 4, Nebraska reached a settlement under which the power utilities would get to build Grayrocks dam by agreeing to purchase some habitat for the whooping crane.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On January 23, 1979, the Endangered Species Committee met for the first time, refused to exempt the snail darter from protection, and granted Grayrocks an exemption from the whooping crane protections.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The most important change that was brought about by the 1978 amendment was the creation of the Endangered Species Committee, known as the "God Squad" because of the substantial impact of its decisions on the natural world.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] One or more temporary members, sharing a single vote, may also be appointed by the President to represent any states that are affected by the exemption in question.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This committee has the authority to exempt a project or action from Section 7 requirements, which otherwise prohibit actions that are "likely to jeopardize the continued existence" of a listed species or its habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] To exempt an action, at least five members must vote in favor of the exemption.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] 4. neither the federal agency or the exemption applicant made irreversible commitment to the resources.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Additionally, mitigation efforts must be taken to reduce the negative effects on the endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The amendments also contain provisions for the Secretary of Defense or the President to authorize exemptions, in cases of national security or disaster situations respectively.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Conversely, the Secretary of State may overrule exemptions if they are found to violate any international treaties.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In 1991, a federal judge ordered the halting of logging on Pacific Northwest national lands because of the threat to the northern spotted owl.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Following this action, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) filed for exemption from Section 7.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The northern spotted owl is a medium-sized bird that is dependent on old-growth forest and large territories for survival.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM came up with a solution that allowed logging to continue in the area, which included the sale of timber on 44 timber tracts to the logging industry.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The 44 tracts totaled 4400 acres (18 km2) of land.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The God Squad convened and discussed the issue.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] In a 5:2 vote, the God Squad voted for approval of the exemption in thirteen of the sales where there was no reasonable alternative to the sale.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] However, the exemption was soon overturned when Judge Stephen Reinhardt on the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals found it had been illegal for the President to talk to his cabinet about the exemption.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The environmentalists and the BLM agreed on a compromise that allowed the timber sale to continue.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The BLM would develop a Long Range Forest Management Plan that would need to be approved by the FWS before any future timber sales.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] When the Clinton administration came into office, they withdrew the exemption request and convened a conference resulting in appointment of the Forest Ecosystem Management Assessment Team (FEMAT).
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The FEMAT was created to develop a plan to protect the owl while still maintaining logging and forest management across the region.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] FEMAT and the Clinton administration agreed to protect 10 million acres (40,000 km2) of old growth forest for the owl, while limiting logging to 1 billion board feet (2,400,000 m3) per year.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] On March 31, 2026, a meeting of the God Squad voted to exempt oil and gas mining companies operating in the Gulf of Mexico from the Endangered Species Act, on unspecified national security grounds.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] The decision was requested by US Secretary of Defense Pete Hegseth.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] A similar announcement earlier in the month resulted in a lawsuit that adequate public notice was not provided.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] Environmental advocates were concerned the decision could cause the extinction of Rice's whale, which only lives in the Gulf of Mexico and is critically endangered after population loss caused by the Deepwater Horizon oil spill.
[src:endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978/endangered-species-act-amendments-of-1978] This decision overrides mitigation measures such as slowing down boats in whale habitat, keeping a safe distance from whales, and using quieter air guns for seismic surveys.
